0001   0000             ; ESP8266 TCP/IP UNAPI BIOS v.1.3
0002   0000             ; PICOVERSE UART version
0003   0000             ; Oduvaldo Pavan Junior
0004   0000             ; ducasp@gmail.com
0005   0000             ;    This code implements TCP/IP UNAPI Specification for MSX-SM
0006   0000             ;
0007   0000             ; Pieces of this code were based on DENYOTCP.ASM (Denyonet ROM)
0008   0000             ; made by Konamiman
0009   0000             ;
0010   0000             ; This code also has contributions from KdL, most specifically in the Wi-Fi
0011   0000             ; setup menus and functionality, he has helped quite a lot to get it to the
0012   0000             ; final format and functionality, thanks!
0013   0000             ;
0014   0000             ; The MSX PICO version of this code has contribution from Jeroen Taverne That
0015   0000             ; helped making some MACROs on the fixed / non speed optimized loop I/O parts
0016   0000             ; of the code so we can easily switch this from I/O based to Memory Based.
0017   0000             ;
0018   0000             ; Note: this implementation depends upon ESP8266 having the UNAPI
0019   0000             ; firmware flashed. This firmware has been developed by me as well.
0020   0000             ;
0021   0000             ; Usage is free as long as you publish your code changes. If you make a profit
0022   0000             ; selling something using this code, a suggestion is that you donate one or two
0023   0000             ; pieces of the hardware to the MSX DEV contest to be awarded to MSX DEV winners
0024   0000             ; as this shouldn't cost much and perhaps will bring interest on developers to
0025   0000             ; make games that support internet :)
0026   0000             ;
0027   0000             ; Design details:
0028   0000             ; There are five instances of this ROM
0029   0000             ;
0030   0000             ; 1 - If configured as disabled in set-up menu item 4, or through setting F2
0031   0000             ;     device to EF or keeping DEL pressed during boot, it won't load at all.
0032   0000             ; 2 - F1 is pressed during boot, or through setting F2 device to F1, it will
0033   0000             ;     show a setup menu, ESC resume boot.
0034   0000             ; 3 - F2 is pressed during a soft reset, or trhough setting F2 device to F2 it
0035   0000             ;     will force re-set of the ESP and re-connection to the AP.
0036   0000             ; 4 - No key is pressed during a warm boot and F2 device is set to F0, UNAPI 
0037   0000             ;     is enabled (default), EXTBIO HOOK for UNAPI calls is installed and HTIM_I
0038   0000             ;     hook for internal usage and a few bytes at top of TPA are reserved upon
0039   0000             ;     the first UNAPI function being called. No ESP reset or tries to set-up the
0040   0000             ;     the RTC are done, so it is a quick warm-boot.
0041   0000             ; 5 - No key is pressed during a cold boot or F2 is set to FE or any unknown
0042   0000             ;     value, UNAPI is enabled (default), EXTBIO HOOK for UNAPI calls is installed
0043   0000             ;     and HTIM_I hook for internal usage and a few bytes at top of TPA are reserved
0044   0000             ;     upon the first UNAPI function being called. ESP is reset and if BIOS is set
0045   0000             ;     up to do so, SNTP connection attempt is made and RTC is updated
0046   0000             ;
0047   0000             ; As a ROM, our segment is read only, so for RAM needs we need to use RAM not
0048   0000             ; in our page. This ROM will do the following:
0049   0000             ;
0050   0000             ; If running the SETUP menu, we are going to "borrow" BASIC program area, that
0051   0000             ; is saved at TXTTAB. We can't allocate memory at this point as any possible
0052   0000             ; disk rom might be sitting on a slot that has not been initialized and results
0053   0000             ; could be bad. The BASIC program area trick should be safe, unless some other
0054   0000             ; cartridge runs a BASIC software for something (i.e.: wait disks be initialized
0055   0000             ; ), in such case, that BASIC software or trick will most likely be corrupted
0056   0000             ; after running our setup.
0057   0000             ;
0058   0000             ; After boot, we need RAM in the 4th page. We have the SLOT WORK AREA for free,
0059   0000             ; it is 8 bytes reserved for our slot, and that is certainly not enough, just
0060   0000             ; the EXTBIOS HOOK backup cost us 5 bytes, so we have three bytes remaining. Of
0061   0000             ; those, we use two to indicate the bottom of the memory reserved in the 4th
0062   0000             ; page. Whenever more memory is needed, HIMEM_RESERVED_SIZE must change, just
0063   0000             ; remember that more memory reserved means less memory available to
0064   0000             ; applications and BASIC, so use it wisely.
0065   0000             ;
0066   0000             ; Slot Work Area Details
0067   0000             ; 0000 - 0004   : EXTBIO hook backup
0068   0000             ; 0005 - 0006   : HIMEM Allocated area (starts with 00 xx, once allocated goes
0069   0000             ;                 to Fxxx or Exxx so checking 0005 if 00 is enough)
0070   0000             ; 007           : Unused
0071   0000             ;
0072   0000             ; Current HIMEM mapping offset related to the address stored in the 6th and 7th
0073   0000             ; bytes of our slot work area:
0074   0000             ;
0075   0000             ; 0000 - 0004   : HTIM_I hook backup
0076   0000             ; 0005 - 0006   : Counter that our HTIM_I hook updates
0077   0000             ; 0007          : Store Single Byte some functions need
0078   0000             ; 0008          : Stores whether DNS is ready or not
0079   0000             ; 0009 - 000A   : Stores last DNS result
0080   0000             ; 000B - 000C   : Stores a 16 bits value
0081   0000             ; 000D - 0012   : Store a backup of BC / DE / HL
0082   0000             ;   000D - 000E : C and B
0083   0000             ;   000F - 0010 : D and E
0084   0000             ;   0011 - 0012 : H and L
0085   0000             ; 0013 - 001D   : Unused
0086   0000             ;
0087   0000             ; As this is sitting on a slot, there is a resoanable chance that this is initialized
0088   0000             ; before any disk controllers. If that is the case, allocating memory at HIMEM is bad
0089   0000             ; and might have two bad behaviors:
0090   0000             ;
0091   0000             ; 1 - Disk Controller is smart enough to determine HIMEM was moved and simply do not
0092   0000             ; initialize. No disk available...
0093   0000             ; 2 - Disk Controller doesn't care and simply wipe-out memory below original HIMEM at
0094   0000             ; boot to create the disk interfaces static work area, thus, causing our allocated
0095   0000             ; memory to be overwritten and MSX will most likely crash on ther first VDP interrupt
0096   0000             ; after that...
0097   0000             ;
0098   0000             ; So, allocating memory at cartridge startup will make MSX freeze or misbehave or not
0099   0000             ; have the disk available if our ROM is sitting in a slot lower than the disk. There
0100   0000             ; are a few possibilities:
0101   0000             ;
0102   0000             ; 1 - Hook to H_STKE, it is called once all slots have been initialized... But, using
0103   0000             ; this hook will make ESE SCSI to not work and halt with a "No enough memory" message,
0104   0000             ; so I do not consider it a good option as the intention is to re-use code for other
0105   0000             ; adapters.
0106   0000             ; 2 - On any UNAPI call check the slot work area if the allocated area is other than 00
0107   0000             ; and if it is, execute, otherwise, first execute our allocation routine. This has an
0108   0000             ; overhead of a dozen instructions at every UNAPI function we execute, does not seem to
0109   0000             ; impact performance compared to the UNAPI RAM driver that doesn't has it
0110   0000             ; 3 - Try to go crazy and check for dos roms on slots above us, initialize those first
0111   0000             ; if found... Too much trouble for a dozen instructions.
0112   0000             ;
0113   0000             ; So, for the moment the design decision is option #2
0114   0000             ;
0115   0000             ; F2 Device by KdL
0116   0000             ; That device, present on recent OCM implementations, allow a byte to be saved and
0117   0000             ; read from IO address F2. It has FF on start-up, and KdL devised the following
0118   0000             ; values/states:
0119   0000             ;
0120   0000             ; FF - Default, meaning cold boot
0121   0000             ; FE - Set this when an unexpected error occurred
0122   0000             ; F2 - Equivalent to keeping F2 pressed at boot time, force the next warm boot
0123   0000             ;      to try to detect the ESP8266
0124   0000             ; F1 - Will force the Wi-Fi setup at next warm boot, so it is not needed to
0125   0000             ;      keep F1 pressed
0126   0000             ; F0 - Means that RTC has date and time, so the next warm boot doesn't check
0127   0000             ;      for F1/F2 or try to update RTC, being faster
0128   0000             ; EF - Set when ESP8266 was not found or by user at runtime to disable UNAPI
0129   0000             ;      next warm boot
0130   0000             ;
0131   0000             ; PICOVERSE also implements the F2 device
0132   0000             
0133   0000             ;*************************
0134   0000             ;***  BUILD DEFINITIONS **
0135   0000             ;*************************
0136   0000             
0137   0000             ;--- verbose rom...?
0138   0000             NON_VERBOSE_ROM:        equ 0
0139   0000             ;--- Use memory mapped IO or not...
0140   0000             USE_MEM_IO:             equ 1
0141   0000             
0142   0000             ;*******************
0143   0000             ;***  CONSTANTS  ***
0144   0000             ;*******************
0145   0000             
0146   0000             ;--- System variables and routines:
0147   0000             CHGMOD:                 equ #005F
0148   0000             CHSNS:                  equ #009C
0149   0000             CHGET:                  equ #009F
0150   0000             CHPUT:                  equ #00A2
0151   0000             BEEP:                   equ #00C0
0152   0000             SNSMAT:                 equ #0141
0153   0000             KILBUF:                 equ #0156
0154   0000             LINLEN:                 equ #F3B0
0155   0000             CLIKSW:                 equ #F3DB
0156   0000             REG2SAV:                equ #F3E1
0157   0000             REG4SAV:                equ #F3E3
0158   0000             TXTTAB:                 equ #F676
0159   0000             ARG:                    equ #F847
0160   0000             HOKVLD:                 equ #FB20
0161   0000             HIMEM:                  equ #FC4A
0162   0000             CSRSW:                  equ #FCA9
0163   0000             EXPTBL:                 equ #FCC1
0164   0000             SLTWRK:                 equ #FD09
0165   0000             H_TIMI:                 equ #FD9F
0166   0000             H_CLEA:                 equ #FED0
0167   0000             EXTBIO:                 equ #FFCA
0168   0000             
0169   0000             
0170   0000             ;--- Memory ports:
0171   0000             MEM_OUT_CMD_PORT:       equ #7F06
0172   0000             MEM_OUT_TX_PORT:        equ #7F07
0173   0000             MEM_IN_DATA_PORT:       equ #7F06
0174   0000             MEM_IN_STS_PORT:        equ #7F07
0175   0000             MEM_PORT_F2:            equ #7F05
0176   0000             
0177   0000             ;--- I/O ports:
0178   0000             OUT_CMD_PORT:           equ #06
0179   0000             OUT_TX_PORT:            equ #07
0180   0000             IN_DATA_PORT:           equ #06
0181   0000             IN_STS_PORT:            equ #07
0182   0000             PORT_F2:                equ #F2
0183   0000             
0184   0000             
0185   0000                 if USE_MEM_IO = 1
0186   0000               MACRO SET_SPEED
0187   0000~                xor a
0188   0000~                ld  (MEM_OUT_CMD_PORT),a            ; Clear UART
0189   0000               ENDM
0190   0000             
0191   0000                 MACRO WRITE_CMD_PORT_A
0192   0000~                    ld  (MEM_OUT_CMD_PORT),a
0193   0000                 ENDM
0194   0000             
0195   0000               MACRO CLEAR_UART
0196   0000~                ld  a,20
0197   0000~                ld  (MEM_OUT_CMD_PORT),a            ; Clear UART
0198   0000               ENDM
0199   0000             
0200   0000               MACRO SEND_DATA
0201   0000~                ld  (MEM_OUT_TX_PORT),a             ; Just send, no need to wait response
0202   0000               ENDM
0203   0000             
0204   0000               MACRO RECEIVE_DATA
0205   0000~                ld a,(MEM_IN_DATA_PORT)
0206   0000               ENDM
0207   0000             
0208   0000               MACRO LOAD_STS_PORT_IN_A
0209   0000~                ld  a,(MEM_IN_STS_PORT)
0210   0000               ENDM
0211   0000             
0212   0000               MACRO CHECK_DATA
0213   0000~                ld  a,(MEM_IN_STS_PORT)
0214   0000~                bit 0,a                         ; If nz has data
0215   0000               ENDM
0216   0000             
0217   0000               MACRO CHECK_QUICK_RECEIVE
0218   0000~                ld  a,(MEM_IN_STS_PORT)
0219   0000~                bit 3,a                         ; Quick Receive Supported?
0220   0000               ENDM
0221   0000             
0222   0000               MACRO CHECK_BUFFER_UNDERRUN
0223   0000~                ld  a,(MEM_IN_STS_PORT)
0224   0000~                bit 4,a                         ; Buffer underrun?
0225   0000               ENDM
0226   0000             
0227   0000               MACRO READ_F2
0228   0000~                ld  a,(MEM_PORT_F2)
0229   0000               ENDM
0230   0000             
0231   0000               MACRO WRITE_F2
0232   0000~                ld  (MEM_PORT_F2),a
0233   0000               ENDM
0234   0000                 else
0235   0000~            
0236   0000~              MACRO SET_SPEED
0237   0000~                xor a
0238   0000~                out (OUT_CMD_PORT),a            ; Clear UART
0239   0000~              ENDM
0240   0000~            
0241   0000~                MACRO WRITE_CMD_PORT_A
0242   0000~                    out (OUT_CMD_PORT),a
0243   0000~                ENDM
0244   0000~            
0245   0000~              MACRO CLEAR_UART
0246   0000~                ld  a,20
0247   0000~                out (OUT_CMD_PORT),a            ; Clear UART
0248   0000~              ENDM
0249   0000~            
0250   0000~              MACRO SEND_DATA
0251   0000~                out (OUT_TX_PORT),a             ; Just send, no need to wait response
0252   0000~              ENDM
0253   0000~            
0254   0000~              MACRO RECEIVE_DATA
0255   0000~                in a,(IN_DATA_PORT)
0256   0000~              ENDM
0257   0000~            
0258   0000~              MACRO LOAD_STS_PORT_IN_A
0259   0000~                in  a,(IN_STS_PORT)
0260   0000~              ENDM
0261   0000~            
0262   0000~              MACRO CHECK_DATA
0263   0000~                in  a,(IN_STS_PORT)
0264   0000~                bit 0,a                         ; If nz has data
0265   0000~              ENDM
0266   0000~            
0267   0000~              MACRO CHECK_QUICK_RECEIVE
0268   0000~                ld  a,(IN_STS_PORT)
0269   0000~                bit 3,a                         ; Quick Receive Supported?
0270   0000~              ENDM
0271   0000~            
0272   0000~              MACRO CHECK_BUFFER_UNDERRUN
0273   0000~                in  a,(IN_STS_PORT)
0274   0000~                bit 4,a                         ; Buffer underrun?
0275   0000~              ENDM
0276   0000~            
0277   0000~              MACRO READ_F2
0278   0000~                in  a,(PORT_F2)
0279   0000~              ENDM
0280   0000~            
0281   0000~              MACRO WRITE_F2
0282   0000~                out (PORT_F2),a
0283   0000~              ENDM
0284   0000                 endif
0285   0000             
0286   0000             ;--- API version and implementation version:
0287   0000             API_V_P:                equ 1
0288   0000             API_V_S:                equ 2
0289   0000             ROM_V_P:                equ 1
0290   0000             ROM_V_S:                equ 3
0291   0000             
0292   0000             ;--- Size of memory to reserve in upper TPA:
0293   0000             HIMEM_RESERVED_SIZE     equ 30
0294   0000             
0295   0000             ;--- Layout of our TPA area:
0296   0000             H_TIM_BACKUP_OFFSET     equ 0
0297   0000             MEMORY_COUNTER_OFFSET   equ 5
0298   0000             MEMORY_SB_VAR_OFFSET    equ 7
0299   0000             MEMORY_DNS_READY_OFFSET equ 8
0300   0000             MEMORY_DNS_RES_OFFSET   equ 9
0301   0000             MEMORY_DB_VAR_OFFSET    equ #0B
0302   0000             MEMORY_REGBACKUP_OFFSET equ #0D
0303   0000             MEMORY_BCBACKUP_OFFSET  equ #0D
0304   0000             MEMORY_DEBACKUP_OFFSET  equ #0F
0305   0000             MEMORY_HLBACKUP_OFFSET  equ #11
0306   0000             
0307   0000             ;--- Scan Page Size
0308   0000             SCAN_MAX_PAGE_SIZE      equ 8
0309   0000             
0310   0000             ;--- Maximum number of available standard and implementation-specific function
0311   0000             ;--- numbers. Must be 0 to 127.
0312   0000             MAX_FN:                 equ 29
0313   0000             
0314   0000             ;--- Must be either zero (if no implementation-specific functions available),
0315   0000             ;--- or 128 to 254.
0316   0000             MAX_IMPFN:              equ 0
0317   0000             
0318   0000             ;--- TCP/IP UNAPI error codes:
0319   0000             ERR_OK:                 equ 0
0320   0000             ERR_NOT_IMP:            equ 1
0321   0000             ERR_NO_NETWORK:         equ 2
0322   0000             ERR_NO_DATA:            equ 3
0323   0000             ERR_INV_PARAM:          equ 4
0324   0000             ERR_QUERY_EXISTS:       equ 5
0325   0000             ERR_INV_IP:             equ 6
0326   0000             ERR_NO_DNS:             equ 7
0327   0000             ERR_DNS:                equ 8
0328   0000             ERR_NO_FREE_CONN:       equ 9
0329   0000             ERR_CONN_EXISTS:        equ 10
0330   0000             ERR_NO_CONN:            equ 11
0331   0000             ERR_CONN_STATE:         equ 12
0332   0000             ERR_BUFFER:             equ 13
0333   0000             ERR_LARGE_DGRAM:        equ 14
0334   0000             ERR_INV_OPER:           equ 15
0335   0000             
0336   0000             ;--- TCP/IP UNAPI connection Status
0337   0000             UNAPI_TCPIP_NS_CLOSED   equ 0
0338   0000             UNAPI_TCPIP_NS_OPENING  equ 1
0339   0000             UNAPI_TCPIP_NS_OPEN     equ 2
0340   0000             UNAPI_TCPIP_NS_UNKNOWN  equ 255
0341   0000             
0342   0000             ;************************
0343   0000             ;***  MSX ROM HEADER  ***
0344   0000             ;************************
0345   0000                 org #4000
0346   4000 41 42           db                  #41,#42
0347   4002 10 40           dw                  INIT        ; Initialize ESP, if not found, won't install hook
0348   4004 00 00           dw                  0           ; Statement
0349   4006 00 00           dw                  0           ; Device
0350   4008 00 00           dw                  0           ; Text
0351   400A 00              ds                  6           ; Reserved
0352   4010             
0353   4010             ;==================
0354   4010             ;===  Start-up  ===
0355   4010             ;==================
0356   4010             
0357   4010             INIT:
0358   4010 7C              ld  a,h                         ; Let's test if we are mirrored and being executed in wrong page
0359   4011 FE 40           cp  #40                         ; is MSB 0x40?
0360   4013 C0              ret nz                          ; if not, return, it is a mirror
0361   4014                 ; Let's set some System Variables
0362   4014 AF              xor a                           ; a = #00
0363   4015 32 A9 FC        ld  (CSRSW),a                   ; cursor display is disabled
0364   4018 32 DB F3        ld  (CLIKSW),a                  ; when key press, key click disabled
0365   401B                 ; Let's intercept [DEL] key
0366   401B 3E 08           ld  a,8
0367   401D CD 41 01        call    SNSMAT
0368   4020 CB 5F           bit 3,a                         ; Test [DEL]
0369   4022 C8              ret z                           ; If DEL is pressed, UNAPI driver is not loaded and exits
0370   4023                 ; Let's check the Screen Mode, ref. https://www.msx.org/wiki/VDP_Table_Base_Address_Registers
0371   4023 3A E1 F3        ld  a,(REG2SAV)
0372   4026 FE 02           cp  2
0373   4028 CA 32 40        jp  z,SCREEN_SETUP              ; If yes, is SCREEN 3
0374   402B 3A E3 F3        ld  a,(REG4SAV)
0375   402E FE 00           cp  0
0376   4030 28 06           jr  z,IS_SCREEN1                ; If yes, is SCREEN 1
0377   4032             SCREEN_SETUP:
0378   4032                 ; Let's set the SCREEN 1
0379   4032 3E 01           ld  a,1                         ; a = #01
0380   4034 F7              rst #30
0381   4035 00              db  0
0382   4036 5F 00           dw  CHGMOD                      ; SCREEN 1
0383   4038             IS_SCREEN1:
0384   4038 3E 1D           ld  a,29                        ; WIDTH 29
0385   403A 32 B0 F3        ld  (LINLEN),a
0386   403D                 ; We check if the Port F2 device is available
0387   403D                 READ_F2                         ; a = #FF, default value if it comes from power off or hard reset
0387   403D 3A 05 7F    >    ld  a,(MEM_PORT_F2)
0388   4040 2F              cpl                             ; a = #FF - a
0389   4041 4F              ld  c,a                         ; c = #00
0390   4042                 WRITE_F2                        ; a = #00
0390   4042 32 05 7F    >    ld  (MEM_PORT_F2),a
0391   4045                 ; Wait 250ms to ensure a successful hard reset even if you press the button very quickly
0392   4045 CD F1 49        call    WAIT_250MS_AND_THEN_CONTINUE
0393   4048                 READ_F2                         ; a = #00?
0393   4048 3A 05 7F    >    ld  a,(MEM_PORT_F2)
0394   404B 2F              cpl                             ; a = #FF - a
0395   404C                 WRITE_F2                        ; a = #FF?
0395   404C 32 05 7F    >    ld  (MEM_PORT_F2),a
0396   404F F5              push    af
0397   4050 3E FE           ld  a,#FE                       ; Preset #FE, unexpected error
0398   4052                 WRITE_F2                        ; on port #F2
0398   4052 32 05 7F    >    ld  (MEM_PORT_F2),a
0399   4055 F1              pop af
0400   4056 B9              cp  c                           ; If not a = c, port #F2 is writable and available
0401   4057 28 3D           jr  z,BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF       ; If a = c, port #F2 is not available, let's proceed as "boot from power off"
0402   4059                 ; Ok, Port F2 device available
0403   4059 FE EF           cp  #EF                         ; UNAPI driver has been disabled
0404   405B 20 04           jr  nz,NOT_DISABLED_BY_F2       ; No, let's continue checking
0405   405D                 WRITE_F2                        ; If yes, UNAPI driver is not loaded and exits, but need to restore F2 port to not have a false error
0405   405D 32 05 7F    >    ld  (MEM_PORT_F2),a
0406   4060 C9              ret                             ; And our work is done
0407   4061             NOT_DISABLED_BY_F2:
0408   4061 FE F0           cp  #F0                         ; UNAPI driver has been loaded at least once
0409   4063 C2 78 40        jp  nz, F2_IS_NOT_F0            ; Ok, has not been loaded
0410   4066                 ; Let's intercept [F1] key
0411   4066 3E 06           ld  a,6
0412   4068 CD 41 01        call    SNSMAT
0413   406B CB 6F           bit 5,a                         ; Test [F1]
0414   406D CA 38 42        jp  z,ENTERING_ESPSETUP         ; If F1 is pressed, let's execute our setup menu
0415   4070                 ; F1 is not pressed, continue
0416   4070 CB 77           bit 6,a                         ; Test [F2]
0417   4072 C2 E9 40        jp  nz,INIT_UNAPI               ; If F2 is not pressed, let's proceed to INIT_UNAPI
0418   4075                 ; F2 is not pressed, continue
0419   4075 C3 A2 41        jp  INIT_NOCLOCKUPDAT2          ; If yes, proceed without affecting the connection or the date and time
0420   4078             F2_IS_NOT_F0:
0421   4078 FE F1           cp  #F1                         ; User requested to go directly to Wi-Fi Setup
0422   407A CA 38 42        jp  z,ENTERING_ESPSETUP         ; If yes, let's execute our setup menu
0423   407D FE F2           cp  #F2                         ; User forces to check if ESP is installed
0424   407F CA C5 40        jp  z,F2_IS_PRESSED             ; If yes, let's go check it out
0425   4082 FE FE           cp  #FE                         ; Unexpected error from the previous reboot
0426   4084 20 10           jr  nz,BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF      ; If no one is confirmed, let's proceed as "boot from power off"
0427   4086                 ; Oops! An unexpected error occurred on the last reboot
0428   4086 21 E5 69        ld  hl,STR_OOPS                 ; Print Oops! An unexpected error message
0429   4089 CD 80 4C        call    PRINTHL                 ; and let's proceed as "boot from power off"
0430   408C 06 78           ld  b,120                       ; Wait 2 seconds with message on screen
0431   408E             WAIT_2S:
0432   408E 76              halt
0433   408F 10 FD           djnz    WAIT_2S                 ; If not zero, our time out has not elapsed
0434   4091 3E 0C           ld  a,CLS
0435   4093 CD A2 00        call    CHPUT
0436   4096             BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF:
0437   4096                 ; Let's intercept [F1] key
0438   4096 3E 06           ld  a,6
0439   4098 CD 41 01        call    SNSMAT
0440   409B CB 6F           bit 5,a                         ; Test [F1]
0441   409D CA 38 42        jp  z,ENTERING_ESPSETUP         ; If F1 is pressed, let's execute our setup menu
0442   40A0                 ; F1 is not pressed, continue
0443   40A0                 if  NON_VERBOSE_ROM = 0
0444   40A0 21 BD 5D        ld  hl,WELCOME
0445   40A3 CD 80 4C        call    PRINTHL
0446   40A6                 CHECK_QUICK_RECEIVE
0446   40A6 3A 07 7F    >    ld  a,(MEM_IN_STS_PORT)
0446   40A9 CB 5F       >    bit 3,a                         ; Quick Receive Supported?
0447   40AB 20 08           jr  nz,BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF.1    ; QR Supported
0448   40AD 21 29 5E        ld  hl,WELCOME_SF2
0449   40B0 CD 80 4C        call    PRINTHL
0450   40B3 18 06           jr  BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF.2
0451   40B5             BOOT_FROM_POWER_OFF.1:
